[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(2) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "The unbelieving Jews stirred up the Gentiles . . .",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—It is the distinguishing feature of nearly all the persecutions in the Acts that they originated in the hostility of the Jews. The case of Demetrius furnishes almost the only exception (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 19:24",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and even there the Jews apparently fomented the enmity of the Greek craftsmen. So at a considerably later date (A.D. 169) we find them prominent in bringing about the persecution which ended in the death of Polycarp at Smyrna (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Mart. Polyc.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " c. 13).",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Acts 14:2-4",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Acts 14:2-4",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "But the unbelieving Jews ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Who were greatly provoked at the growing success of the gospel, and studied all they could to put a stop to its progress; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "stirred up the Gentiles ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— The idolatrous Gentiles, the heathen inhabitants of the place; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "and made their minds evil affected ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Greek, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "εκακωσαν τας ψυχας",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "irritated; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "or, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "exasperated their souls against the brethren ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Against the disciples of Christ, and especially against those celebrated teachers of a religion against which they had imbibed strong prejudices. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Long time, therefore, abode they ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Namely, Paul and Barnabas; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "speaking boldly in the Lord ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Because the minds of the Gentiles were so filled with prejudice and malignity against them, one would have thought, that therefore they should have withdrawn and hastened out of the way; or, if they had preached, should have preached cautiously, for fear of giving further provocation to those who were already sufficiently enraged: no, but the contrary; therefore they abode there a long time, speaking boldly in the Lord: the more they perceived the spirit and rancour of the town against the new converts, the more they were animated to go on in their work, and the more needful they saw it to continue among them, to confirm them in the faith, and to comfort them. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Who gave testimony unto the word of his grace ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Which they delivered, working with them according to his promise, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Lo, I am with you always: and granted signs and wonders to be done by their hands ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Which were of great use to confirm the faith of the new converts, and to prevail with many others to receive the gospel, and which might have convinced all the inhabitants, if they had exercised a becoming candour. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "But the multitude of the city was divided ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Into two parties, and both very active and vigorous: among the rulers and persons of rank, and among the common people, there were some that ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "held with the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "unbelieving ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Jews, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "and others that held with the apostles. It seems this business of the preaching of the gospel was so universally taken notice of with concern, that almost every adult person, even of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "the multitude of the city, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "was either for it or against it; none stood neuter: all were either for them or their enemies; for God or Baal; for Christ or Beelzebub.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "14:1-7 The apostles spake so plainly, with such evidence and proof of the Spirit, and with such power; so warmly, and with such concern for the souls of men; that those who heard them could not but say, God was with them of a truth. Yet the success was not to be reckoned to the manner of their preaching, but to the Spirit of God who used that means. Perseverance in doing good, amidst dangers and hardships, is a blessed evidence of grace. Wherever God's servants are driven, they should seek to declare the truth. When they went on in Christ's name and strength, he failed not to give testimony to the word of his grace. He has assured us it is the word of God, and that we may venture our souls upon it. The Gentiles and Jews were at enmity with one another, yet united against Christians. If the church's enemies join to destroy it, shall not its friends unite for its preservation? God has a shelter for his people in a storm; he is, and will be their Hiding-place. In times of persecution, believers may see cause to quit a spot, though they do not quit their Master's work.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
