  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Expositor's Greek Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 14:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἀπειθοῦντες",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", see critical notes. If we read ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἀπειθήσαντες",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", “that were disobedient,” R.V., but ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "cf.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 3:36",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and Page’s note ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "in loco",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Lumby quotes ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Bar 1:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and regards the expression here as stronger than “unbelieving,” rather unbelief breaking forth into rebellion, as in the case of these Jews at Iconium and elsewhere. Ramsay renders “the disaffected”.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἐκάκωσαν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ": “exasperated,” Ramsay; only here in N.T. in this sense, five times in Acts, once in quotation; only once elsewhere in N.T., ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Peter 3:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "cf.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " for its use here Jos., ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Ant.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", xvi., 1, 2; vii., 3; viii., 6. It is used several times in LXX, but not in this sense, the nearest approach to it is Psalms 105 :(LXX)32. The same phrase occurs twice, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 29:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Numbers 30:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", but with a different meaning or reading in D. See critical notes.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
